name: Lely core libraries
description:
The Lely core libraries are a collection of libraries designed to support the implementation robot control applications, on Linux, Windows or bare metal platforms. The primary components are an event loop/task scheduling mechanism, an I/O abstraction layer, and an extensive implementation of the CANopen protocol. The libraries have no external dependencies (apart from optional BlueZ headers on Linux).

The libraries are used to control sensors and actuators in all the recent robots made by Lely.

name: Medical Imaging Diagnosis Assistant
description:
The goal of this project is to propose a new methodology for fully automated breast cancer detection and segmentation from multi-modal medical images introducing clinical covariates. This protocol provides the following novelties. First, it lies on the use of deep convolutional neural networks (CNNs) that will incorporate several image modalities: 3D magnetic resonance images (MRI), ultrasound (US) or Mammography (MG) views. This is the first methodology that is able to classify a whole exam, containing all the above image modalities.

In this project, we are interested to develop a new assistant (i.e. a system that will provide diagnosis support as a second opinion), for other human tissues, besides the breast. This will embrace other anatomies such as the aorta, spinal column, epicardial fat, body fat, heart, lungs, and muscle.

Example: {"branch":"HEAD","caller":"main.go:72","commit":"v0.8.1","msg":"MetalLB speaker starting version 0.8.1 (commit v0.8.1, branch HEAD)","ts":"2019-08-27T04:37:31.972293077Z","version":"0.8.1"}

Release notes are linked off the website's homepage. They are also pointed to with each release announcement.

https://metallb.universe.tf/release-notes/
report_responses_justification: Bugs are acknowledged within the specified timeframe, and usually also fixed in that timeframe. Feature requests and requests for free labor in the form of tech support may not be answered in that timeframe.
report_archive_justification: Issue tracker keeps a record of bugs, feature requests, and discussions. https://github.com/danderson/metallb/issues
vulnerability_report_private_justificati: Vulnerabilities can be disclosed on the issue tracker, or by non-encrypted email to the author. The project doesn't have a pipeline for secure disclosure at this time.
build_justification: MetalLB uses https://www.pyinvoke.org as a build system. https://metallb.universe.tf/community/ describes how to build the code.
build_common_tools_justification: MetalLB uses Invoke, an open-source task orchestration system.
test_justification: MetalLB is written in go and uses standard `go test` tests.
test_most_justification: We aim for widespread code coverage, and most source packages have extensive tests.
tests_are_added_justification: Example of a new feature in MetalLB 0.8.0: https://github.com/danderson/metallb/pull/314/files . The change to the code includes tests covering the new behavior.
warnings_justification: Tests are run with the race condition detector enabled. We also run lint tools. Go itself doesn't have any warnings, the compiler only ever reports errors.
warnings_fixed_justification: Race conditions, and lint errors cause CI failure and require fixing. The Go language has no concept of compile warnings, so that's N/A.
warnings_strict_justification: We enable all lint warnings that have acceptable signal-to-noise ratio.
static_analysis_justification: gometalinter with a variety of checks.
static_analysis_common_vulnerabilities_j: There are no FLOSS tools that I'm aware of that do this for Go code.
static_analysis_fixed_justification: No vulnerabilities ever found or reported.
dynamic_analysis_justification: Optional criterion. Would be nice to have, but I'm not made of time or money.
dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification: Go is a memory safe language.
dynamic_analysis_enable_assertions_justi: The software includes a lot of internal consistency self-checks that are always run, even in production, and the software fails safe if such an assertion is tripped.
dynamic_analysis_fixed_justification: No vulnerabilities reported. Disclosure guidelines talk about prompt fixes.
test_continuous_integration_justificatio: CI at https://circleci.com/gh/danderson/metallb/tree/master . Also does continuous deployment of test binaries.
discussion_justification: https://metallb.universe.tf/community/ lists 4 communication methods: Slack (proprietary, but accessible through a browser UI), IRC, a mailing list, and Github issues/pull requests.
english_justification: https://metallb.universe.tf is all in English, and all project communication happens in English.

https://github.com/hyperledger/besu/blob/master/docs/development/building.md#run-tests
test_most_justification:
Some not all of the code branches, input fields and functionality are covered.

https://github.com/hyperledger/besu/blob/master/docs/development/code-coverage.md
test_policy_justification:
Formalised in the coding conventions, using indirect language i.e. referring to 'well tested' being by unit, integration or acceptance test appropriate for the feature.

https://github.com/hyperledger/besu/blob/master/CODING-CONVENTIONS.md#32-creating-code-for-constant-refactoring-and-evolving-design
tests_are_added_justification: PR approval is the evidence, as Pull Request review include whether there are sufficient tests for the code being added / amended.
tests_documented_added_justification:
The GitHub PR template (displayed to the when they raise a propose a change) contains a link to the contributing guidelines (they cite the requirement for test coverage)
```
<!-- Thanks for sending a pull request! Please check out our contribution guidelines: -->
<!-- https://github.com/hyperledger/besu/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md -->
```
warnings_justification:
The build tool applies Google ErrorProne to the codebase (performed in CI on master and PR builds)

https://github.com/google/error-prone
warnings_fixed_justification: On rule violation ErrorProne is set to cause an error that ceases the build.
warnings_strict_justification:
In addition to the standard ErrorProne rules, custom rules have been added to Besu.

https://github.com/hyperledger/besu/tree/master/errorprone-checks
static_analysis_justification: We use error-prone, Snyk, Google java style formatter and enforce it for every checkin.  We also treat all compiler warnings as errors.
test_continuous_integration_justificatio:
All commits to master and PRs trigger a CI build and test, currently performed on Jenkins (although the migration to another is being considered, with direction from HLF).

https://jenkins.pegasys.tech/job/Besu/
discussion_justification: The community can engage with chat with the project at chat.hyperledger.org or https://lists.hyperledger.org/g/besu
hardened_site_justification: Found all required security hardening headers.

name: Open Alliance for Cloud Adoption
description:
The OACA is community-led Linux Foundation project to enable innovative, safe and agile use of cloud computing for business value. 

OACA is driven by the mission to share cloud adoption practices and continuously improve maturity, security, and optimize cloud usage. 

Our goal is to create a highly engaged and vibrant community of cloud practitioners collaborating to drive interoperability of practices and creation of value.
